{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox football tournament season | year = 1955 | title = Chatham Cup | dates = {{nowrap|3 September 1955}} | venue = [[Basin Reserve]], [[Wellington]] | num_teams = | champions = [[Western A.F.C.|Western]] (4th&nbsp;title) | runner-up = [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] | champ_match_score = 6 – 2 | prevseason = [[1954 Chatham Cup|1954]] | nextseason = [[1956 Chatham Cup|1956]] }} The '''1955 Chatham Cup''' was the 28th annual nationwide knockout [[association football|football]] competition in [[New Zealand]].
The competition was run on a regional basis, with regional associations each holding separate qualifying rounds.
Teams taking part in the final rounds are known to have included [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] (Auckland), [[Huntly Thistle]], [[Eastern Union]] (Gisborne), [[New Plymouth Old Boys]], [[Napier Rovers]], [[Wanganui Athletic]], [[Kiwi United]] (Manawatu), [[Masterton Athletic]], [[Victoria University (soccer)|Victoria University]], [[Western A.F.C.|Western]] (Christchurch), and [[Roslyn-Wakari]] (Dunedin).
==The 1955 final== In the final, winger Peter Saunderson became the seventh player to score a finals [[hat-trick]]. Western's total of six goals equalled [[Waterside (Wellington)|Waterside]]'s tally from the [[1940 Chatham Cup|1940 final]], and the aggregate of eight goals also equalled the record set in that final. The game was played in a howling Wellington southerly, and Western made full use of it in the first half, rattling in four goals. John White and [[Alex Davis]] had both scored in the opening dozen minutes, and these were added to by both Saunderson and Stan Ralph. In the second half Anderson and King reduced the deficit to two before Saunderson scored a further brace to seal the win for the southerners.<ref>{{HiltonNZAssoc}} p.72</ref> King's goal was his sixth in Chatham Cup finals, after a hat-trick in the [[1951 Chatham Cup|1951 Final]] and two more in [[1953 Chatham Cup|1953]].
